**Solution outline**

The sum can be rewritten using the symmetry of binomial coefficients  

\[
S(n,k)=\sum_{j=k}^{\,n-k}\binom nj\binom n{\,n-j\,}
      =\sum_{j=k}^{\,n-k}\binom nj^{2}.
\]

Since  

\[
\sum_{j=0}^{n}\binom nj^{2}= \binom{2n}{n},
\]

we have  

\[
S(n,k)=\binom{2n}{n}-2\sum_{j=0}^{k-1}\binom nj^{2}.
\]

For the required values

\[
\begin{aligned}
S(10000,4)&=\displaystyle\binom{20000}{10000}
            -2\Bigl[\binom{10000}{0}^{2}
                   +\binom{10000}{1}^{2}
                   +\binom{10000}{2}^{2}
                   +\binom{10000}{3}^{2}\Bigr],\\[4pt]
S(9998,5)&=\displaystyle\binom{19996}{9998}
           -2\Bigl[\binom{9998}{0}^{2}
                  +\binom{9998}{1}^{2}
                  +\binom{9998}{2}^{2}
                  +\binom{9998}{3}^{2}
                  +\binom{9998}{4}^{2}\Bigr].
\end{aligned}
\]

The correction terms are only the squares of a few small binomial
coefficients; they are astronomically small compared with the central
binomial coefficient \(\binom{2n}{n}\) (they are of order \(10^{-6000}\)).
Hence we may replace each \(S\) by the corresponding central binomial
coefficient with an error far below \(10^{-100}\).

Therefore

\[
I=\frac{S(10000,4)}{S(9998,5)}
   \approx\frac{\displaystyle\binom{20000}{10000}}
                {\displaystyle\binom{19996}{9998}}
   =\frac{19997\cdot19998\cdot19999\cdot20000}
          {(10000\cdot9999)^{2}}
   =\frac{4(2n-3)(2n-1)}{n(n-1)}\Big|_{n=10000}
   =\frac{399\,920\,003}{24\,997\,500}
   =15.9983999600\ldots
\]

The omitted corrections are of order \(10^{-5988}\) and cannot change the
first twelve decimal places of \(I\).

Hence  

\[
100I=100\cdot15.9983999600\ldots=1599.83999600\ldots
\]

and the greatest integer not exceeding this value is  

\[
\boxed{1599}.
\]
